<fr:tree
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"
toc="true"
numbered="true"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="true"
expanded="true"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>333</fr:anchor><fr:addr>hodge-theory-i</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-i.xml</fr:route><fr:title>Hodge Theory I</fr:title></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>
  P. Deligne.
  "Théorie de Hodge I".
  <fr:em>Actes du Congrès intern. math.</fr:em> <fr:strong>1</fr:strong> (1970) pp. 425–430.
  <fr:link
href="https://publications.ias.edu/node/359"
type="external">publications.ias.edu/node/359</fr:link></fr:p><fr:p>
  We intend to give a heuristic dictionary between statements in <fr:tex>l</fr:tex>-adic cohomology and statements in Hodge theory.
  This dictionary has as its most notable sources <fr:link
href="S1960.xml"
type="local"
addr="S1960">[S1960]</fr:link> and the conjectural theory of Grothendieck motives <fr:link
href="D1969.xml"
type="local"
addr="D1969">[D1969]</fr:link>.
  Up until now, it has mainly served to formulate conjectures in Hodge theory, and it has sometimes even suggested a proof.
</fr:p><fr:tree
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"
toc="true"
numbered="false"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="false"
expanded="true"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>248</fr:anchor><fr:addr>hodge-theory-i-1</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-i-1.xml</fr:route><fr:number>1</fr:number><fr:parent>hodge-theory-i</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:tree
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"
toc="true"
numbered="true"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="false"
expanded="true"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>246</fr:anchor><fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon><fr:addr>hodge-theory-i-definition-1.1</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-i-definition-1.1.xml</fr:route><fr:number>1.1</fr:number><fr:parent>hodge-theory-i-1</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>
    A <fr:em>mixed Hodge structure</fr:em> <fr:tex>H</fr:tex> consists of

    
 <html:ol
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">
      
 <html:li
style="list-style-type: &quot; a.  &quot;">
        a <fr:tex>\mathbb {Z}</fr:tex>-module <fr:tex>H_ \mathbb {Z}</fr:tex> of finite type (the "<fr:em>integer lattice</fr:em>");
      </html:li>

      
 <html:li
style="list-style-type: &quot; b.  &quot;">
        a finite increasing filtration <fr:tex>W</fr:tex> of <fr:tex>H_ \mathbb {Q} =H_ \mathbb {Z} \otimes \mathbb {Q}</fr:tex> (the "<fr:em>weight filtration</fr:em>");
      </html:li>

      
 <html:li
style="list-style-type: &quot; c.  &quot;">
        a finite decreasing filtration <fr:tex>F</fr:tex> of <fr:tex>H_ \mathbb {C} =H_ \mathbb {Z} \otimes \mathbb {C}</fr:tex> (the "<fr:em>Hodge filtration</fr:em>").
      </html:li>

    </html:ol>


    This data is subject to the following condition:
    there exists a (unique) bigradation of <fr:tex>\operatorname {Gr} _W(H_ \mathbb {C} )</fr:tex> by subspaces <fr:tex>H^{p,q}</fr:tex> such that

    
 <html:ol
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">
      
 <html:li
style="list-style-type: &quot; i.  &quot;">
        <fr:tex>\operatorname {Gr} _W^n(H_ \mathbb {C} )= \bigoplus _{p+q=n}H^{p,q}</fr:tex>
      </html:li>

      
 <html:li
style="list-style-type: &quot; ii.  &quot;">
        the filtration <fr:tex>F</fr:tex> induces on <fr:tex>\operatorname {Gr} _W(H_ \mathbb {C} )</fr:tex> the filtration
        <fr:tex
display="block">            \operatorname {Gr} _W(F)^p           =  \bigoplus _{p' \geq  p} H^{p',q'}         </fr:tex>
      </html:li>

      
 <html:li
style="list-style-type: &quot; iii.  &quot;">
        <fr:tex>\overline {H^{pq}}=H^{qp}</fr:tex>.
      </html:li>

    </html:ol></fr:p></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree><fr:p>
  A <fr:em>morphism</fr:em> <fr:tex>f \colon  H \to  H'</fr:tex> is a homomorphism <fr:tex>f_ \mathbb {Z} \colon  H_ \mathbb {Z} \to  H'_ \mathbb {Z}</fr:tex> such that <fr:tex>f_ \mathbb {Q} \colon  H_ \mathbb {Q} \to  H'_ \mathbb {Q}</fr:tex> and <fr:tex>f_ \mathbb {C} \colon  H_ \mathbb {C} \to  H'_ \mathbb {C}</fr:tex> are compatible with the filtrations <fr:tex>W</fr:tex> and <fr:tex>F</fr:tex> (respectively).
</fr:p><fr:tree
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"
toc="true"
numbered="true"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="false"
expanded="true"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>247</fr:anchor><fr:taxon>Equation</fr:taxon><fr:addr>hodge-theory-i-equation-1.2</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-i-equation-1.2.xml</fr:route><fr:number>1.2</fr:number><fr:parent>hodge-theory-i-1</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>
    The <fr:em>Hodge numbers</fr:em> of <fr:tex>H</fr:tex> are the integers
    <fr:tex
display="block">       h^{pq} =  \dim  H^{pq} = h^{qp}.     \tag{1.2}     </fr:tex></fr:p></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree><fr:p>
  We say that <fr:tex>H</fr:tex> is pure <fr:em>of weight <fr:tex>n</fr:tex></fr:em> if <fr:tex>h^{pq}=0</fr:tex> for <fr:tex>p+q \neq  n</fr:tex> (i.e. if <fr:tex>\operatorname {Gr} _W^i(H)=0</fr:tex> for <fr:tex>i \neq  n</fr:tex>).
  We also say that <fr:tex>H</fr:tex> is a <fr:em>Hodge structure of weight <fr:tex>n</fr:tex></fr:em>.
</fr:p><fr:p>
  The <fr:em>Tate Hodge structure</fr:em> <fr:tex>\mathbb {Z} (1)</fr:tex> is the Hodge structure of weight <fr:tex>-2</fr:tex>, of pure type <fr:tex>(-1,-1)</fr:tex>, for which <fr:tex>\mathbb {Z} (1)_ \mathbb {C} = \mathbb {C}</fr:tex> and <fr:tex>\mathbb {Z} (1)_ \mathbb {Z}  = 2 \pi  i \mathbb {Z}  =  \operatorname {Ker} ( \exp \colon \mathbb {C} \to \mathbb {C} ^*) \subset \mathbb {C}</fr:tex>.
  We set <fr:tex>\mathbb {Z} (n)= \mathbb {Z} (1)^{ \otimes  n}</fr:tex>.
</fr:p><fr:p>
  We can show that mixed Hodge structures form an abelian category.
  If <fr:tex>f \colon  H \to  H'</fr:tex> is a morphism, then <fr:tex>f_ \mathbb {Q}</fr:tex> and <fr:tex>f_ \mathbb {C}</fr:tex> are strictly compatible with the filtrations <fr:tex>W</fr:tex> and <fr:tex>F</fr:tex> (cf. <fr:link
href="hodge-theory-ii-2.3.5"
type="external">[Hodge Theory II, 2.3.5]</fr:link>).
</fr:p></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree><fr:tree
